# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
-  Method 1 :- O( m * (log m) * c ) , where c is the time complexity of the comparator and m is the number of rows.

- Method 2 :- O( m * n * log(m) ), where log(m) is for using Max-Heap.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: 
- Method 1 :- O(1), since no extra space has been taken.

- Method 2 :- O( m * n ) since we are creating a new 2 D matrix.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
// 1st method using Custom Comparator

public int[][] sortTheStudents(int[][] score, int k) {
      Arrays.sort(score,(s1,s2)->s2[k]-s1[k]);
      return score;
}




// 2nd method using Max Heap(priority-queue)

class Solution {
    public int[][] sortTheStudents(int[][] score, int k) {
        int m = score.length;
        int n = score[0].length;

        PriorityQueue<pair> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b)->(b.y-a.y));

        for(int i = 0; i<m; i++){
            for(int j = 0; j<n; j++){
                if(j==k)
                    pq.add(new pair(i,score[i][j]));
            }
        }

        int[][] arr = new int[m][n];

        int j = 0;
        while(!pq.isEmpty()){
            int index = pq.remove().x;

            for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){
                arr[j][i] = score[index][i];
            }
            j++;
        }


        return arr;
    }
}


class pair{
    int x;
    int y;

    pair(int X, int Y){
        this.x = X;
        this.y = Y;
    }
}











```

