# Approach
The Question just needs us to sort the 2D vector accroding to kth row and the rest of data is not affecting the sorting process.

So, we can just sort the data according to jth row.
Below is the implementation in C++ and JAVA.

# Code Explanation
***cmp function*** :
custom sorting function "cmp" which compares two vectors of integers, "a" and "b", based on their last element. The function returns true if the last element of "a" is greater than that of "b", and false otherwise.

Then we record the values of the ith student's score in the jth exam at the end of the corresponding vector in the 2D "score" vector. Then, it sorts the "score" vector based on the custom sorting function "cmp" which compares the last element of each vector in the 2D vector.

After sorting, we remove the recorded jth exam data by popping the last element of each vector in the 2D vector and return the sorted 2D vector as the result.

# C++ Code
```
class Solution {
    // Custom sort for sorting data according to the last element
    // Last element was jth score of ith student
    static bool cmp(vector<int>& a, vector<int>&b) { return a.back()>b.back(); }
public:
    vector<vector<int>> sortTheStudents(vector<vector<int>>& score, int k) {
        // Recording the value of ith student in jth exam at the end
        for (int i=0;i<score.size();i++) score[i].push_back(score[i][k]);
        // Sorting on basis of the ith student in jth exam
        sort(score.begin(),score.end(),cmp);
        // Removing the recorded jth exam data
        for (int i=0;i<score.size();i++) score[i].pop_back();
        // Returning the sorted matrix
        return score;
    }
};
```
# JAVA Code
```
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Comparator;
import java.util.Vector;

class Solution {
    public static Vector<Vector<Integer>> sortTheStudents(Vector<Vector<Integer>> score, int k) {
        // Recording the value of ith student in jth exam at the end
        for (int i=0;i<score.size();i++) score.get(i).add(score.get(i).get(k));
        // Sorting on basis of the ith student in jth exam
        score.sort(new Comparator<Vector<Integer>>() {
            @Override
            public int compare(Vector<Integer> a, Vector<Integer> b) {
                return Integer.compare(b.get(b.size()-1), a.get(a.size()-1));
            }
        });
        // Removing the recorded jth exam data
        for (int i=0;i<score.size();i++) score.get(i).remove(score.get(i).size()-1);
        // Returning the sorted matrix
        return score;
    }
}
```

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
***O(nlogn + n)*** : O(n*Logn) for sorting and O(n) for iterating over the column specified in question.

- Space complexity:
***O(n)*** : Because for every row, one column is added.
